<subSubSection id="D9A56571772DFFD5FF32CE27FE84FE85" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="531" pageId="1" pageNumber="530" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="910036FA772DFFD6FF32CE27FB46FA28" blockId="1.[151,1437,1066,2036]" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FF32CE27FEC6FBDA" bold="true" box="[151,273,1066,1091]" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="56BF4D79772DFFD6FEBDCE26FE74FBDA" authority="Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof, 2018" authorityName="Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof" authorityYear="2018" box="[280,419,1067,1091]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Bernadottea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FEBDCE26FE74FBDA" box="[280,419,1067,1091]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">BernadOttea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are known only from males, whose appearance is generally similar to 
<taxonomicName id="56BF4D79772DFFD6FB1ACE26FAE0FBDB" authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1860" box="[1215,1335,1067,1090]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Winnertzia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FB1ACE26FAE0FBDB" box="[1215,1335,1067,1090]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Winnertzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="09842A7F772DFFD6FAECCE27FA5DFBDA" box="[1353,1418,1066,1091]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1957,1979]" captionTargetBox="[168,1367,353,1926]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[157,1398,339,1930]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Male habitus of Bernadottea natalenSiS. Holotype mounted in Canada balsam, partly rearranged and completed, one set of bodyappendages and parts of vestiture omitted.Scale 0.50 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1175078/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). All 
<taxonomicName id="56BF4D79772DFFD6FF6FCE42FE82FBFE" authority="Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof, 2018" authorityName="Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof" authorityYear="2018" box="[202,341,1103,1127]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Bernadottea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FF6FCE42FE82FBFE" box="[202,341,1103,1127]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">BernadOttea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and many 
<taxonomicName id="56BF4D79772DFFD6FE4ECE42FDB4FBFF" authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1860" box="[491,611,1103,1126]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Winnertzia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FE4ECE42FDB4FBFF" box="[491,611,1103,1126]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Winnertzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have antennae with 10–11 flagellomeres and linear, thread-shaped, multiporous sensilla (
<figureCitation id="09842A7F772DFFD6FE2ECE78FE35FB17" box="[395,482,1141,1166]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1470,1492]" captionTargetBox="[175,1419,209,1438]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1449]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male morphology of Bernadottea natalenSiS (holotype). A: Gonostylus, dorsal. B: Ninth tergite, dorsal. C: Genitalia, ventral.D: Tegmen and ejaculatory apodeme, ventral.E: Fourth flagellomere, lateral.Scales 0.05 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1175080/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
, ↓1). The absence of vein M4 (
<figureCitation id="09842A7F772DFFD6FC9CCE78FC56FB17" box="[825,897,1141,1166]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1957,1979]" captionTargetBox="[168,1367,353,1926]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[157,1398,339,1930]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Male habitus of Bernadottea natalenSiS. Holotype mounted in Canada balsam, partly rearranged and completed, one set of bodyappendages and parts of vestiture omitted.Scale 0.50 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1175078/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Figs 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="09842A7F772DFFD6FC35CE7BFC64FB17" box="[912,947,1142,1166]" captionStart="FIGURE3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1666,1688]" captionTargetBox="[194,1393,211,1605]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1436,193,1645]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE3. Malemorphology ofBernadottea honShuenSiS (holotype).A:Gonostylus,ventral. B: Gonostylus,dorsal.C:Ninth tergite, dorsal. D: Genitalia, ventral. E: Tegmen and ejaculatory apodeme, ventral. F: Third flagellomere, ventrolateral. G: Wing, dorsal.Scales for A–F, 0.05 mm, for G, 0.50 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1175082/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">3G</figureCitation>
) is a character that 
<taxonomicName id="56BF4D79772DFFD6FB31CE78FAC9FB14" authority="Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof, 2018" authorityName="Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof" authorityYear="2018" box="[1172,1310,1141,1165]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Bernadottea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FB31CE78FAC9FB14" box="[1172,1310,1141,1165]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">BernadOttea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
share only with 
<taxonomicName id="56BF4D79772DFFD6FF75CE90FE3AFB2C" authority="Felt, 1920" authorityName="Felt" authorityYear="1920" box="[208,493,1180,1205]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Parwinnertzia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FF75CE90FEA7FB2D" box="[208,368,1181,1204]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Parwinnertzia</emphasis>
Felt, 1920
</taxonomicName>
, a questionably distinct genus as will be discussed below, and a very few species of both 
<taxonomicName id="56BF4D79772DFFD6FF77CECCFE9DFB41" authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1860" box="[210,330,1217,1240]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Winnertzia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FF77CECCFE9DFB41" box="[210,330,1217,1240]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Winnertzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="56BF4D79772DFFD6FE20CECCFD56FB40" authority="Felt, 1911" authorityName="Felt" authorityYear="1911" box="[389,641,1216,1241]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Kronomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FE20CECCFDD5FB41" box="[389,514,1217,1240]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">KrOnOmyia</emphasis>
Felt, 1911
</taxonomicName>
. A peculiarity of 
<taxonomicName id="56BF4D79772DFFD6FCE8CECDFC00FB41" authority="Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof, 2018" authorityName="Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof" authorityYear="2018" box="[845,983,1216,1240]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Bernadottea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FCE8CECDFC00FB41" box="[845,983,1216,1240]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">BernadOttea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is that the male genitalic structures are much more complex compared with other 
<taxonomicName id="56BF4D79772DFFD6FDD1CEE9FCD3FB64" authorityName="Panelius" authorityYear="1965" box="[628,772,1252,1277]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Winnertziini">Winnertziini</taxonomicName>
. This complexity is obvious in the gonostylus, which tends to be bilobed (
<figureCitation id="09842A7F772DFFD6FEE9CF05FE7AFAB8" box="[332,429,1288,1313]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1470,1492]" captionTargetBox="[175,1419,209,1438]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1449]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male morphology of Bernadottea natalenSiS (holotype). A: Gonostylus, dorsal. B: Ninth tergite, dorsal. C: Genitalia, ventral.D: Tegmen and ejaculatory apodeme, ventral.E: Fourth flagellomere, lateral.Scales 0.05 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1175080/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
); the gonocoxites, which are equipped with various, sometimes conspicuously large processes (
<figureCitation id="09842A7F772DFFD6FEB2CF21FEA2FADC" box="[279,373,1324,1349]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1687,1709]" captionTargetBox="[195,1393,363,1626]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[150,1436,327,1666]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Male morphology of Bernadottea pahangenSiS (holotype). A: Gonostylus, dorsal. B: Ninth tergite, dorsal. C: Genitalia, ventral.D: Tegmen and ejaculatory apodeme, ventral.E: Fourth flagellomere, lateral.Scales 0.05 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1175084/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
); the tegmen, which is strongly sclerotized and provided with a whole range of different substructures (
<figureCitation id="09842A7F772DFFD6FE9FCF5DFE43FAF0" box="[314,404,1360,1385]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1470,1492]" captionTargetBox="[175,1419,209,1438]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1449]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male morphology of Bernadottea natalenSiS (holotype). A: Gonostylus, dorsal. B: Ninth tergite, dorsal. C: Genitalia, ventral.D: Tegmen and ejaculatory apodeme, ventral.E: Fourth flagellomere, lateral.Scales 0.05 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1175080/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
); and the ejaculatory apodeme whose apex is closely tied to both the aedeagal bulge and the tegmen through connective links that are partly membranous, partly sclerotized. The great extent of diversity found in male genitalic structures provides the basis for the identification of 
<taxonomicName id="56BF4D79772DFFD6FC02CF95FBE5FA29" authority="Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof, 2018" authorityName="Jaschhof &amp; Jaschhof" authorityYear="2018" box="[935,1074,1432,1456]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Bernadottea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FC02CF95FBE5FA29" box="[935,1074,1432,1456]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">BernadOttea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="910036FA772DFFD5FF62CFB1FE84FE85" blockId="1.[151,1437,1066,2036]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,285]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="531" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FF62CFB1FE73FA4C" bold="true" box="[199,420,1468,1493]" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Other characters.</emphasis>
Body size, including genitalia, 
<quantity id="56479B1F772DFFD6FC92CFB0FC1CFA4D" box="[823,971,1469,1493]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="1" pageNumber="530" unit="mm" value="1.1" valueMax="1.4" valueMin="0.8">0.8–1.4 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FC7ACFB1FBF2FA4C" bold="true" box="[991,1061,1468,1493]" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Head.</emphasis>
Occiput with large, randomly distributed setae. Eye bridge short, 2–5 ommatidia long laterally. Postfrons asetose. Scape slightly larger than pedicel, both with a few setae. Necks of flagellomeres shorter than nodes; nodes completely covered with microtrichia, 1 whorl or double whorl of setae basally, numerous sensory hairs with large, hooded alveoli cumulated ventrally; each flagellomere except terminal with 2 translucent, linear sensilla, one on either side (
<figureCitation id="09842A7F772DFFD6FACACC41FF6DF910" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1470,1492]" captionTargetBox="[175,1419,209,1438]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1449]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male morphology of Bernadottea natalenSiS (holotype). A: Gonostylus, dorsal. B: Ninth tergite, dorsal. C: Genitalia, ventral.D: Tegmen and ejaculatory apodeme, ventral.E: Fourth flagellomere, lateral.Scales 0.05 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1175080/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
). Apical flagellomere normal size or conspicuously long due to fusion of two bodies into a single entity. Palpus shorter than head height (
<figureCitation id="09842A7F772DFFD6FE16CC99FE24F934" box="[435,499,1684,1709]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1957,1979]" captionTargetBox="[168,1367,353,1926]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[157,1398,339,1930]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Male habitus of Bernadottea natalenSiS. Holotype mounted in Canada balsam, partly rearranged and completed, one set of bodyappendages and parts of vestiture omitted.Scale 0.50 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1175078/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), 3-segmented, segments subcylindrical, with setae of various sizes, apical segment longest of all. Labellum small. 
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FE5ACCB5FD88F948" bold="true" box="[511,607,1720,1745]" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Thorax.</emphasis>
Pronotum setose. Scutal setae large, arranged in random bands laterally and dorsolaterally. Scutellum setose. Both anepisternum and anepimeron asetose. 
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FB93CCD1FBA0F96C" bold="true" box="[1078,1143,1756,1781]" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Wing</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="09842A7F772DFFD6FB22CCD1FB19F96C" box="[1159,1230,1756,1781]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1957,1979]" captionTargetBox="[168,1367,353,1926]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[157,1398,339,1930]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Male habitus of Bernadottea natalenSiS. Holotype mounted in Canada balsam, partly rearranged and completed, one set of bodyappendages and parts of vestiture omitted.Scale 0.50 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1175078/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Figs 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="09842A7F772DFFD6FB78CCD0FAD4F96C" box="[1245,1283,1757,1781]" captionStart="FIGURE3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1666,1688]" captionTargetBox="[194,1393,211,1605]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[150,1436,193,1645]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE3. Malemorphology ofBernadottea honShuenSiS (holotype).A:Gonostylus,ventral. B: Gonostylus,dorsal.C:Ninth tergite, dorsal. D: Genitalia, ventral. E: Tegmen and ejaculatory apodeme, ventral. F: Third flagellomere, ventrolateral. G: Wing, dorsal.Scales for A–F, 0.05 mm, for G, 0.50 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1175082/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">3G</figureCitation>
). Wing about as long as body. Venation typical of 
<taxonomicName id="56BF4D79772DFFD6FD95CD0DFD6BF880" authorityName="Panelius" authorityYear="1965" box="[560,700,1792,1817]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="530" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Winnertziini">Winnertziini</taxonomicName>
except for lack of M4. Membrane setose. 
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FB31CD0DFB04F880" bold="true" box="[1172,1235,1792,1817]" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Legs.</emphasis>
All parts covered densely with setae of various sizes and narrow scales. Basitarsi without spines. Claws slightly bent, toothless. Empodia vestigial. 
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FECACD46FE3CF8FD" bold="true" box="[367,491,1867,1892]" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Abdomen.</emphasis>
First to sixth segments of normal size, seventh and eighth segments smaller (
<figureCitation id="09842A7F772DFFD6FAEFCD46FA5CF8FA" box="[1354,1419,1867,1892]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1957,1979]" captionTargetBox="[168,1367,353,1926]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[157,1398,339,1930]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Male habitus of Bernadottea natalenSiS. Holotype mounted in Canada balsam, partly rearranged and completed, one set of bodyappendages and parts of vestiture omitted.Scale 0.50 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1175078/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), their tergites diminished to strongly sclerotized bars dorsally and small portions laterally. Tergal setae sparse or absent, sternal setae numerous, large. Pleural membrane setose or asetose, varying among species. 
<emphasis id="A3CBEAE8772DFFD6FB45CD9EFA81F835" bold="true" box="[1248,1366,1939,1964]" pageId="1" pageNumber="530">Genitalia.</emphasis>
Ninth tergite long, covering more than half of genitalia’s dorsal surface; posterior edge bilobed. Gonocoxites longer than wide; ventral emargination at least partly reinforced by sclerotization, either V- or U-shaped; parts of ventral surface usually darkly pigmented; dorsal apodemes thin, usually long. Gonostylus multiform, with 1 or 2 pectinate claws. Tegmen multiform, large, longer than wide. Ejaculatory apodeme nearly as long as gonocoxites, strong, typically with fine, pipette-like apex. Hypoproct and cerci typical for 
<taxonomicName id="56BF4D79772EFFD5FC17CAD2FB95FF61" authorityName="Panelius" authorityYear="1965" box="[946,1090,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="531" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Winnertziini">Winnertziini</taxonomicName>
, both protruding beyond ninth tergite (
<figureCitation id="09842A7F772EFFD5FF48CB09FE91FE85" box="[237,326,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1470,1492]" captionTargetBox="[175,1419,209,1438]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1449]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male morphology of Bernadottea natalenSiS (holotype). A: Gonostylus, dorsal. B: Ninth tergite, dorsal. C: Genitalia, ventral.D: Tegmen and ejaculatory apodeme, ventral.E: Fourth flagellomere, lateral.Scales 0.05 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1175080/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="531">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
